n full. Based throughout on original research (including newly discovered material) this is a vivid and compelling narrative of a movement which mobilised three million people at its height. The author deftly intertwines analysis and narrative, interspersing his chapters with short ‘Chartist Lives’, relating the intimate and personal to the realm of the social and political. This book will become essential reading for anyone with an interest in early Victorian Britain, specialists, students and general readers alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChartism. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aChartism.  aChartist leaders.  aFeargus O'Connor.  aThe People's Charter.  aanti-Semitism.  ablatant careerism.  acultural dimensions.  apersonal dishonesty.  apolitical charlatanry.  apolitical history.  apolitical mobilization.  aracism.1 aChase, Malcolm, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779136840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847791368423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847791368/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles